author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Haiti is in the grip of a worsening humanitarian crisis, with nearly 700,000 children displaced over the past year due to escalating gang violence. Armed groups now control large parts of the country, leaving public services in ruins and forcing families into overcrowded camps. Many children face violence, food insecurity, and a lack of basic necessities. The killing of President Jovenel Moise in 2021 triggered a power vacuum, worsening the instability.
The United Nations has deployed a Kenyan-led multinational security mission, but it is severely underfunded. UNICEF estimates $250 million is urgently needed to provide aid to Haiti’s 3.3 million children in desperate need, including one million facing critical food shortages. As efforts to curb the violence falter, families continue to suffer.

Al Jazeera's Teresa Bo reports.

Burkina Faso’s Security Minister Mahamadou Sana said the eight people arrested worked for the International NGO Safety Organisation (INSO), a Netherlands-based group specialising in humanitarian safety.
Those detained included a French man, a French-Senegalese woman, a Czech man, a Malian and four Burkinabe nationals, Sana said, alleging the staff members had continued working for the organisation after it was banned for three months, for allegedly “collecting sensitive data without authorisation”.
The Hague-based humanitarian organisation issued a statement on Tuesday saying it “categorically” rejected the allegations about its activities in Burkina Faso.

Al Jazeera’s Nicolas Haque reports

description:
UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres praised the diplomatic efforts of the United States, Qatar, and Egypt for achieving an initial ceasefire in Gaza. 
He urged all parties to fully respect the agreement, including the dignified release of captives, and stressed that the bloodshed must end. 
Guterres highlighted the UN’s readiness to provide food, water, medical aid, and shelter, but warned that silencing the guns alone is not enough. 
He called for safe access for humanitarian workers, removal of bureaucratic obstacles, and rebuilding of infrastructure. 
Reflecting on the human cost, he mourned the lives lost, including UN personnel. 
Guterres emphasised the need to address the occupation, recognise Palestinian self-determination, and pursue a two-state solution. 
He concluded that lasting peace in the region depends on diplomacy, not conflict.

Al Jazeera’s James Bays reports from the United Nations.

description:
Residents of Gaza cautiously celebrate news of a ceasefire agreement that offers a glimmer of hope after two years of unrelenting war. 
While the truce marks the first significant breakthrough in months, Israeli bombing continued during the celebrations, underscoring the fragility of the deal. 
For many Palestinians, the ceasefire represents a chance to rebuild their shattered lives, yet the devastation across the enclave remains immense. 
Displaced families express mixed emotions, reflecting both relief at the prospect of peace and uncertainty about the daunting task of recovery.
The truce, brokered with backing from the US and key regional players, aims to bring an end to years of bloodshed. 
However, Gaza’s residents know that the path to lasting peace will require more than an agreement on paper. 
Many are now focused not just on the cessation of violence but on securing humanitarian aid and resources to begin restoring their lives.
